div.div: X2 is an antler soft hammer. X9-10 are bone points. F1 is a bone ring. F2 is a polished/worked rib. This is apparently a continuation of Unit 7957 (excavated 2004), and is described as platform construction. Dry sieved: the sample is fairly small - perhaps around 150 fragments. The vast majority (95%) are from sheep or goat, but cattle are represented by three specimens including a juvenile/(sub)adult molar and an infantile proximal tibia that must belong to different individuals. There is also a single equid incisor, plus four cow-sized scrap fragments, including a worked rib. A piece of antler - probably red deer - was lifted in multiple fragments (bagged together). This may be the â€˜horn coreâ€™ referred to on the unit sheet, measuring 55 x 160 mm in situ. Finally, there are four bones from various sizes of bird. Amongst the sheep/goats, body part representation is very even. All the major long bones (plus metatarsals) include specimens from 1-3 individuals of varying age, with the MNI of 3 being based on distal femora. Hind limbs and fore limbs are generally evenly represented. Unusually for Ã‡atalhÃ¶yÃ¼k, vertebrae and ribs are present in proportion to the appendicular elements (as also noted for 7957), although cranial elements are perhaps underrepresented, with only one mandible, five sheep-sized skull fragments and no teeth, plus a hyoid. A complete sheep right hind foot - from the astragalus to 3rd phalanges - is present but was not noted as articulated by the excavators. Other taxa are too few to allow comment on body part representation. The degree of fragmentation is variable. Amongst the dry-sieved material most specimens are between 20 and 100mm, with a median of around 50-60mm. A complete sheep metatarsal and the worked cow-sized rib are greater than 100mm. Around half the material is diagnostic, with very few indeterminate specimens but a fair amount of rib/long bone/vertebra scrap. Long bone shafts are generally broken into fragments between 40 and 70mm long while around half of articular ends are complete, suggesting marrow breakage but without especially intensive processing for grease. The articulated sheep foot is an exception, having all elements intact, and may well thus have been treated differently from the bulk of the material. Vertebrae are remarkably intact, often missing only the tips of processes. All groups are represented. Most vertebrae have refittable epiphyses and the colouration of the fusion planes suggests that these were still attached until excavation, indicating minimal disturbance following burial. Amongst the sheep-sized ribs, heads/proximal shafts dominate, with remarkably few blade splinters. The majority of the former are broken off between 4 and 6 cm from the articulation, and almost all have multiple light transverse cut-marks to the lateral face of the shaft just above the break. This is suggestive of a consistent butchery pattern, and it is of course possible that all derive from a single animal. Two sheep-sized rib heads (one with cut marks) refit to a thoracic vertebra. Surface condition is good: most specimens are at condition 2 (â€˜very slight weatheringâ€™) with around 20% at condition 3 (â€˜slight weatheringâ€™) and only two at condition 4 (â€˜moderate weatheringâ€™). Colouring/patination is also remarkably uniform, with almost all specimens being a light yellow, although a few show patches of darker staining. Gnawing, digestion and burning all appear completely absent in the dry-sieved material. Cut marks are rare apart from on the ribs (see above). Flotation sample #2, >4mm, 100% sorted, recorded completely: the flotation material is consistent with the dry-sieved sample, but also reveals an appreciable amount of fish (17 small specimens), micromammalia (18 specimens), and a further nine small bird specimens. Average fragment size is, of course, smaller (median ~20mm) but surface condition is again both good and consistent. There is no sign of gnawing, but three digested specimens are present. There is a low level of burning (<5%). Most burnt specimens are carbonized sheep-sized long bone fragments, although there is also a piece of cattle-sized rib. The only other cattle-sized specimen is a lateral malleolus in fresh condition. Element representation is similar to the main sample but with a larger proportion of vertebrae, cranial fragments and carpals. The excavators suggest an origin as either imported midden material or a house clearance episode. The bone material strongly favours the latter: surface taphonomy, refits and range of elements all point to a high integrity deposit, the bulk of which probably derives from a small number of sheep/goat/sheep-sized individuals. The few equid/cattle/cattle-sized specimens do not fit into this pattern at all: they include portions that are rare or absent amongst the sheep-sized material and generally have worse surface condition with slightly darker patination. It is thus quite possible that they are secondarily-deposited additions to an otherwise high-integrity unit. On the question of continuity between 14460 and 7957, the units are similar in overall composition with some differences in elements and/or sides present, e.g. sheep(sized) mandibles are common in 7957 but rare in 14460. Taking the two together, sheep-sized body part representation would be even more even, with little increase in MNI - perhaps a sign that they are complementary. On the other hand, while both units are very fresh this is especially true of 14460. Colouration is generally slightly darker in 7957, which also has much more root-marking. 7954 may also be the same unit, but while many specimens match the fresh yellow appearance of 14460, a much larger proportion (~20%) have a substantially darker patination. No articulations or refits could be found between 14460 and either of the other mentioned units.
